Key Match Events: Australia defeats England by 36 runs in T20 World Cup at Kensington Oval in Bridgetown
Travis Head and David Warner set the mark for an imposing total of 7-201 as Australia's openers savaged the English attack
Adam Zampa struck for the first of his two wickets with his very first ball, dismissing Phil Salt for 37 off 23 balls
Post-Match Reflections: Mitch Marsh expressed pride in the team's resilience after the win
Jos Buttler reflected on England's struggles outside the powerplay and the bowling performance of Adam Zampa and the pacers
Miscellaneous Highlights: The game was played at the historic Kensington Oval in Bridgetown, Barbados
Australia had only won one of its last seven T20 matches against England coming into the T20 World Cup clash
Others: The stunning 70-run opening partnership between David Warner (39 off 16) and Travis Head (34 off 18) from just 30 balls set the mark for an imposing total

Moeen Ali's first over went for just three runs, but the ill-advised choice to throw the ball to part-time offy Will Jacks did not pay off, as Head smashed his first two balls for six and Warner served up a third in a 22-run bludgeoning of his one and only over

Mitch Marsh (35 off 25), Glenn Maxwell (28 off 25) and Marcus Stoinis (30 off 17) all continued the assault on England's bowlers, of whom only Jofra Archer (1-28) and Moeen Ali (1-18) looked a genuine threat
